dismissalText.commentary: Michael Hussey c Taylor b McMillan 42 (96b 4x4 0x6 135m) SR: 43.75

dismissalComment.html: big big wicket! McMillan bowls on a good length on off stump, Hussey goes for the drive and ends up hitting it on the up to Taylor at cover who dives forward to take a sharp catch, Fleming's decision to use McMillan pays off at once

dismissalText.commentary: Brad Hodge c Fleming b Vettori 22 (49b 2x4 0x6 62m) SR: 44.89

dismissalComment.html: Fleming fumbles and then takes it! Hodge tries to cut once again and gets a thick edge on it, it flies quickly at stomach height to Fleming at first slip who doesn't take it cleanly at the first attempt, he manages to grab it as the ball bounces off his palms

headshotImage.caption: Shane Bond player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Shane Bond player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: Bond strikes, Jaques sees a short ball outside off stump moving away from him and decides to smash it, he goes on the back foot and reaches far out for the ball, the ball hits the toe end of the bat and spoons to Vettori at cover who takes the simplest of catches, perhaps the nerves got to Jaques

headshotImage.caption: BJ Haddin headshot
headshotImage.longCaption: BJ Haddin headshot

dismissalComment.html: bowled him! Bond pitches that just outside off stump and the ball swings in a long way, Haddin tries to hit it through the off side and plays all around it, the ball blasts between bat and pad and smashes into the stumps

headshotImage.caption: Cameron White player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Cameron White player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: You will not see a better caught and bowled! Bond bowls a slower ball full to White who drives back at the bowler, the ball flies low and to the right of Bond who is going the other way on his follow through, he stretches out his right hand and picks up the ball inches off the ground, rolls over and holds on, absolutely stunning catch, pure reflexes!

headshotImage.caption: Nathan Bracken player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Nathan Bracken player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: Bond lets a yorker rip, but it's a slower ball, Bracken backs away and tries to squeeze it on the off side, he misses and Bond hits the stumps, Australia are in shambles

headshotImage.caption: Brad Hogg player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Brad Hogg player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: Bond bowls the slower ball on middle stump, Hogg moves towards the off side and tries to run it past short fine leg, he misses and the ball hits wood, Bond finishes with five for 23

commentTextItems.html: Vincent does it with panache! He picks a fullish delivery on off and middle and swings it over square leg for a flat and powerful six, New Zealand have hammered Australia

commentPostTextItems.html: It's been 22 years since New Zealand last had an opening-stand of over hundred against Australia. Australia have been defeated by ten wickets for the first time in ODI history today. They were missing five key players - Ponting, Gilchrist, Clarke, Lee and Symonds - but they have been humiliated.

The New Zealand bowlers - Shane Bond in particular - made a difficult pitch look unplayable. The Australian batsmen were very subdued and didn't build any momentum. Lou Vincent and Stephen Fleming batted aggressively from the start of the chase and that made a lot of difference.

Here's another interesting fact, if Australia go on to lose the Chappell-Hadlee series, South Africa will move ahead of them as the No 1 ranked team on ODIs. It will be the first time Australia have been dethroned since the ratings were introduced by the ICC in 2002.

Shane Bond is the obvious choice for the Man of the Match. He bowled superbly right through and returned figures of 5 for 23. I've enjoyed bringing today's game to you. Keep a watch on Cricinfo for updates on Oram's finger. Thank you for all your emails and do join us on Sunday for the second ODI at Auckland. This is George Binoy signing off. Cheers!

commentTextItems.html: Johnson fires in short and Vincent takes his eyes off the ball and turns his back on it, it thuds into his back
drifts on to leg stump and Fleming clips it off his pads to deep backward square leg
fuller length on middle and off stump, Vincent pushes it to mid-off and runs a quick single
Vincent smashes a short and wide ball through point for four more, just eight needed now
fuller length on middle and off stump, driven to midwicket on the front foot
full ball on the pads, flicked to Hussey at midwicket

commentTextItems.html: Flemign comes down the pitch, takes the ball on the full and chips it in the air and in the gap at deep midwicket, that wasn't very well controlled but the placement was perfect
driven down to long on for a single
bowled flat but slower through the air outside off stump, Vincent gets across and tries to flick but misses
played fine down to fine leg for a couple of runs

commentPreTextItems.html: David writes in with this "It really has to be said that New Zealand's World Cup preparation is suffering due to a lack of decent competition from their opponents in the Chappell Hadlee series." Wonder what he's talking about!

commentTextItems.html: defended on the front foot on the leg side
full and on the pads, Fleming leans forward and clips it off his pads down to the fine leg fence, the proverbial bread and butter

commentPreTextItems.html: There have been a lot of questions on whether Australia have ever lost an ODI by ten wicket. Well Travis confirms that they haven't, so this could be the first time. New Zealand have won only once by ten wickets before.
